QUESTION: 
1. Create a new GitHub repository.
Clone the repository to your local machine using SSH (generate an SSH key if needed, add the public key to your GitHub account).
Create a new branch named after your username (e.g., Tutedude).
Add your Flask project files to this branch.
Commit the changes and merge the branch into the main branch.


ANSWER:
### Git and GitHub Assignment

First, I created a new repository on GitHub. After that, I generated an SSH key (if it was not already available) and added the public key to my GitHub account. Then, I cloned the repository to my local machine using the SSH URL.

```bash
git clone git@github.com:your-username/your-repository.git
cd your-repository
```

Next, I created a new branch using my username and switched to it.

```bash
git checkout -b Tutedude
```

After creating the branch, I copied my Flask project files into the repository folder. Then, I added all the files to Git, committed the changes, and pushed the branch to GitHub.

```bash
git add .
git commit -m "Added Flask project files"
git push -u origin Tutedude
```

Finally, I merged the `Tutedude` branch into the `main` branch.

```bash
git checkout main
git merge Tutedude
git push origin main
```

This completed the process of creating the repository, working on a separate branch, adding the Flask project, and merging the changes into the main branch.
